Analysis of Project Split Story Usage and Patterns

Introduction

This report analyzes the projects process patterns indicated by split user stories.

Software development and maintenance projects that use an agile life-cycle, such as Scrum, document their requirements as User Stories. These stories are intended to describe a small software feature that is:
1. Understandable to the customer/user,
2. Can be implemented during one sprint (time-boxed delivery period), and
3. Can be tested or demonstrated.

User stories that have not yet been implemented are maintained in a list called a backlog and are subject to change as the customer/user needs change.

An active user story is a user story that is being implemented during the currently active sprint. Once a user story becomes active, it becomes a promise from the software developer to the customer/user to implement the user story and demonstrate it at the end of the sprint.

When a promise (active user story) cannot be delivered during the current sprint and the customer/user still wants the user story to be delivered, then the incomplete user story becomes a split story, that is, a deferred promise.

Split stories come in three varieties:

  • Summary split stories where multiple previously incomplete stories are combined together into one story,
  • Clone split stories where active but incomplete stories are re-designated with a new label and assigned to another (future) sprint,
  • Single split stories where stories are partially completed during a sprint and the incomplete parts of the stories are assigned to another (future) sprint.

The existence of splits stories does not necessarily represent an issue for a project. For example,

  • If agreed between the customer/user and the project, the project may plan to be aggressive in the user stories to which it commits. This aggressiveness will sometimes result in split stories.
  • Due to circumstances outside its control, such as unplanned work interruptions, active user stories may not be completed during the promised sprint, resulting in split stories.

How Split Stories Are Measured and Analyzed in this Report

There are four measurements that are collected with respect to the projects split stories:

  • The maximum number of split stories that the project should have during any sprint.
    • This measurement is called the split story upper specification limit (USL) and is determined by agreement between customer/user and the project. This is sometimes called the voice of the customer.
    • Exceeding the split story USL indicates that, in the customer/users perspective, the project is unacceptably failing to keep its promises.
      • The project may have fewer split stories than the USL without repercussions.
  • The minimum number of split stories that the project should have during any sprint.
    • This measurement is call the split story lower specification limit (LSL) and is determined by agreement between the customer/user and the project. This is sometimes called the voice of the customer.
    • Falling below the split story LSL indicates that, in the customer/users perspective, the project is not being aggressive enough in planning for active stories during a sprint.
      • The split story LSL is typically not a hard threshold measurement, since the project may sometimes be aggressive in planning and still fulfill all active user stories. The split story LSL might be used as an indicator for greater or lesser planning aggressiveness on the part of the project by the customer/user.
      • The minimum value for the split story LSL is zero.
      • The split story LSL is subject to artificial manipulation by a developer who might choose to satisfy the metric by intentionally failing to complete a story.
  • The maximum number of split stories the project should have started or finished during a sprint, based on the projects past performance.
    • This measurement is call the split story upper control limit (UCL) and is determined by statistically characterizing the projects past performance. The split story UCL is sometimes called the voice of the process.
    • Exceeding the split story UCL for either split stories started or finished during a sprint indicates that the project is deviating from its typical performance. That is, the projects process is discordant with the voice of the process as historically demonstrated by the project.
    • Exceeding the split story UCL is a strong but not an absolute indicator of a process problem. For this report, the threshold used in the analysis was set so that exceeding the split story UCL is a 99% chance indicator that a real process problem exists.
  • The minimum number of split stories that the project should have started or finished during a sprint, based on the projects part performance.
    • This measurement is call the split story lower control limit (LCL) and is determined by statistically characterizing the projects past performance. The split story LCL is sometimes called the voice of the process.
    • The split story LCL is not typically of interest for a project. It is not included in this report.

Next Steps

Out-of-bounds conditions for sprint starts indicate that an unusual amount of work is being promised to a customer, while out-of-bounds conditions for sprint ends indicate that an unusual amount of work is finished during one sprint.

  • Using the graphs and tables above, determine all of the starting and ending sprints that had out-of-bounds conditions.
  • Determine if the out-of-bounds conditions were caused by:
    • Conditions outside the projects control, such as unexpected changes in staffing or customer-driven interruptions. If this was the case, use a Failure Modes & Effects Analysis (FMEA) to help the project identify, analyze, and manage surprises.
    • Conditions within the projects control, such as not understanding the implications of multiple user stories (for instance, taking on user stories in areas where project personnel do not collectively have experience), changes in or deviations from a process, wrapping up a set of user stories that have accumulating and are waiting for final completion, or adopting new tools. If this is the case, use root cause analysis tools such as the five whys and Ishikawa diagrams to identify and eliminate the root cause(s) of the condition.

Analysis Model Verification

To be complete, the question of How accurate is teh analysis described above? must be answered.
The analysis uses the Poisson distribution to model the projects split story behavior.
The description and graphs shown below provide insight into the applicability of the Poisson distribution to each type of split with out-of-bounds conditions.
The graphs are Quantile-Quantile plots. If you are unfamiliar with this type of graphical analysis, refer to Appendix A for interpretation information.

Cloners Split Story Starts Analysis Model Verification

Clone split stories are stories that are duplicated from a previously documented story and renamed with a new story identifier. The Poisson Quantile-Quantile Plot for Clone Split Story Starts provides a graphical representation of the analysis for the number and frequency of Clone type split story starts.

  • For points that fall within the confidence bands (vertical bars), the projects Clone Type split stories are explained with 0.95% confidence by this analysis.
    • Points that are outside the bars mean that the projects behavior is not typical but that the analysis is unable to explain this behavior.
    • If all of the points appear to fall in a straight line above or below the bands, then the project is systematically creating more (points above) or suppressing (points below) Clone type split stories. See Appendix A for assistance in interpreting the patterns illustrated in the plot.
  • However, be cautious. There are too few Clone type split stories to conclusively characterize the projects behavior.

Appendix A: Interpretation of Q-Q Plots

The patterns shown in Q-Q plots show how well the actual data being observed corresponds to the theoretical model used in the analysis. Different shapes indicate deviations between the observations and the theoretical model, which might result in the analysis being conservative (that is, failing to identify real problems) or liberal (that is, imagining problems that do not exist).
The following Q-Q Plot diagnostic is provided courtesy of the SAS Institute, Inc.

Description of Point Pattern Possible Interpretation
All points fall in the bands Theoretical model is a useful analysis for the observed data
All but a few points fall in the bands Outliers in the data
The left end of the pattern falls below the bands; the right end falls above the bands Long tails at both ends of the observed data: under-estimated analysis
The left end of the pattern falls above the bands; the right end falls below the bands Short tails at both ends of the observed data: over-estimated analysis
Curved pattern with slope increasing from left to right Observed data is right-skewed: over-estimated analysis
Curved pattern with slope decreasing from left to right Observed data is left-skewed: under-estimated analysis
